</section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-5">Single Variable Distributions: Histograms and Boxplots</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Single variable — univariate — plots are a standard way to start an analysis and the histogram is a go-to plot (<a href="https://www.andata.at/en/software-blog-reader/why-we-love-the-cdf-and-do-not-like-histograms-that-much.html" target="_self">although it has some issues</a>) for graphing a distribution. Here, using my Medium article statistics (you can see <a href="https://medium.com/analyzing-medium-story-stats-with-python-24c6491a8ff0" target="_self">how to get your own stats here</a> or use <a href="https://github.com/WillKoehrsen/Data-Analysis/tree/master/medium" target="_self">mine here</a>) let’s make an interactive histogram of the number of claps for articles ( <code>df</code> is a standard Pandas dataframe):</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
